out things and then I checked it

00:45:04.890 --> 00:45:12.020
and I did a lot of -- the poem
from Cavazzi that I quoted

00:45:12.020 --> 00:45:16.120
at the end of the book, where
he's -- it wasn't published,

00:45:16.120 --> 00:45:17.580
it was in his manuscript.

00:45:17.580 --> 00:45:19.340
The first time it's
published is in my book.

00:45:19.340 --> 00:45:23.550
And he says that Njinga is --
you know, he compares Njinga --

00:45:23.550 --> 00:45:26.340
in fact, I could
actually, just a minute --

00:45:26.340 --> 00:45:30.120
yeah, I know I'm going
on, but this is important.

00:45:30.120 --> 00:45:32.970
So just it will take a sec.

00:45:36.390 --> 00:45:44.680
Okay. "Under this rice cloth,
fielded cloth, in the dark tomb

00:45:44.680 --> 00:45:48.970
that you see, Njinga, who
made herself queen of Ndongo

00:45:48.970 --> 00:45:53.030
and Matamba, lies
buried, a dry corpse.

00:45:53.030 --> 00:45:55.940
In this dark tomb that you see,

00:45:55.940 --> 00:45:58.290
here lies the one
who lived to die.

00:45:58.290 --> 00:46:02.440
Here lies the one
who by dying lives.

00:46:02.440 --> 00:46:06.100
In this dark tomb
she hid herself.

00:46:06.100 --> 00:46:09.130
Because of Agrippa
Rome repelled.

00:46:09.130 --> 00:46:12.270
Because of Helen
Greece rebelled.

00:46:12.270 --> 00:46:17.430
Because of Yusodonia
[phonetic] Germany rebelled.

00:46:17.430 --> 00:46:20.610
Because of Hecuba,
Spain rebelled.

00:46:20.610 --> 00:46:24.370
But Ethiopia did not
rebel for Njinga.

00:46:24.370 --> 00:46:29.970
Instead, Njinga overturned,
destroyed and ruined Ethiopia.

00:46:29.970 --> 00:46:34.040
Njinga in death stole
from Heaven's treasure.

00:46:34.040 --> 00:46:37.530
In this tomb her
body is locked up.

00:46:37.530 --> 00:46:42.060
Therefore, we can sing
to a most cunning thief.

00:46:42.060 --> 00:46:46.980
A most cunning thief has stolen
from the treasury of Heaven.

00:46:46.980 --> 00:46:48.960
Njinga outsmarted even death."

00:46:48.960 --> 00:46:51.180
And that's why her
memory lives on.

00:46:51.180 --> 00:46:54.630
So I wanted to contextualize.

00:46:54.630 --> 00:46:58.010
So this letter is in
the manuscript section.

00:46:58.010 --> 00:47:01.160
It was never published
in Cavazzi's book.

00:47:01.160 --> 00:47:02.650
So that's the type of thing.

00:47:02.650 --> 00:47:05.160
You have to really
compare what is, you know,

00:47:05.160 --> 00:47:09.200
the translated version and
then go back to the original

00:47:09.200 --> 00:47:11.120
to make sure you're
not missing anything.

00:47:11.120 --> 00:47:15.820
And there are a lot of
interesting sections of details

00:47:15.820 --> 00:47:19.740
that go into give you
insight into the mind

00:47:19.740 --> 00:47:24.070
of this incredible
woman that assisted me.

00:47:24.070 --> 00:47:25.370
Yes.

00:47:25.370 --> 00:47:26.670
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:47:26.670 --> 00:47:27.970
I mean, this is very exciting.

00:47:27.970 --> 00:47:29.270
She really is.

00:47:29.270 --> 00:47:33.780
You know, I had always
figured, without any doubt.

00:47:33.780 --> 00:47:37.360
You mentioned a couple of
issues [inaudible] before.

00:47:37.360 --> 00:47:40.160
What were some of the other
issues which she was negotiating

00:47:40.160 --> 00:47:44.320
with the Portuguese, and then

00:47:44.320 --> 00:47:45.670
with the Dutch, again
the Portuguese?

00:47:45.670 --> 00:47:46.970
What were some of the --

00:47:46.970 --> 00:47:48.270
&gt;&gt; Professor Heywood: Well,

00:47:48.270 --> 00:47:49.670
the main thing was she
wanted the Portuguese

00:47:49.670 --> 00:47:55.880
to let her retain
the whole of Ndongo,

00:47:55.880 --> 00:47:57.950
the parts that they had taken.

00:47:57.950 --> 00:48:02.320
She wanted them to -- the
Portuguese had put in her place,

00:48:02.320 --> 00:48:08.460
after they had expelled her or
created conditions where she had

00:48:08.460 --> 00:48:10.770
to go into resistance.

00:48:10.770 --> 00:48:16.150
She wanted them to
get rid of the king

00:48:16.150 --> 00:48:17.620
that they had nominated.

00:48:17.620 --> 00:48:18.920
The Portuguese had said

00:48:18.920 --> 00:48:21.010
that Njinga was not
legitimate because --

00:48:21.010 --> 00:48:22.310
[ Inaudible comment ]

00:48:22.310 --> 00:48:23.720
Yeah. Yes, the Angolans

00:48:23.720 --> 00:48:26.230
and Ndongo never,
you know, had women.

00:48:26.230 --> 00:48:30.010
In the book I tried to show
that in this sort of --

00:48:30.010 --> 00:48:35.130
in the traditions of this area
that women were very crucial

00:48:35.130 --> 00:48:37.910
as central players
in the kingship.

00:48:37.910 --> 00:48:42.950
So the thing was to
recognize her legitimacy,

00:48:42.950 --> 00:48:48.490
recognize her rights
to the areas of Angola

00:48:48.490 --> 00:48:53.230
that her brother had left
and her father had left.

00:48:53.230 --> 00:48:54.530
Up to her father's --

00:48:54.530 --> 00:48:57.460
the Portuguese had
moved in up to Ambaca.

00:48:57.460 --> 00:49:00.790
She wanted them to
get, you know, removal.

00:49:00.790 --> 00:49:02.720
Yes. With the Dutch, she hoped

00:49:02.720 --> 00:49:05.010
that the Dutch would just
help her get totally, push --

00:49:05.010 --> 00:49:06.560
[ Inaudible comment ]

00:49:06.560 --> 00:49:09.270
No Portuguese presence
in Angola.

00:49:09.270 --> 00:49:13.010
She also -- I didn't mention
this in the article I'm going

00:49:13.010 --> 00:49:16.340
to write on this diplomacy,
she also had a lot of diplomacy

00:49:16.340 --> 00:49:20.280
with Africans, especially the
King of Congo, and she would,

00:49:20.280 --> 00:49:22.220
in fact -- she was planning --

00:49:22.220 --> 00:49:28.550
she said the only rulers I
respect is the King of Congo.

00:49:28.550 --> 00:49:31.770
So that there were a lot of
things that Njinga was a --

00:49:31.770 --> 00:49:34.980
if there was a -- I'm not
talking about protonationalist.

00:49:34.980 --> 00:49:37.970
She was a nationalist
from the beginning.

00:49:37.970 --> 00:49:40.160
We have these terms
protonational.

00:49:40.160 --> 00:49:42.530
She knew what nationalism was.

00:49:42.530 --> 00:49:45.770
She was the, you know,
ruler of her land.

00:49:45.770 --> 00:49:47.950
So those types of things.

00:49:47.950 --> 00:49:54.290
And she did not want the
Portuguese to come into Matamba

00:49:54.290 --> 00:49:58.990
and -- but through Portuguese
speaking missionaries

00:49:58.990 --> 00:50:01.000
who would be spies
for the Portuguese

00:50:01.000 --> 00:50:02.600
and undermine her rule.

00:50:02.600 --> 00:50:06.510
But she did not mind
using the Portuguese,

00:50:06.510 --> 00:50:10.130
so that she would send them
gifts, she would also send

00:50:10.130 --> 00:50:12.290
to get the church
that she built.

00:50:12.290 --> 00:50:13.950
It was all -- all the interior

00:50:13.950 --> 00:50:19.170
of the church design was all
done by Portuguese and mulatto,

00:50:19.170 --> 00:50:24.430
mixed people, skilled
craftsmen who were in Massangano

00:50:24.430 --> 00:50:27.000
and Luanda, and she paid them.

00:50:27.000 --> 00:50:34.260
So she did not mind, you
know, learning all the new

00:50:34.260 --> 00:50:38.300
or adopting all the new styles,
whether it was in a dress,

00:50:38.300 --> 00:50:40.870
she asked the governor to send
her earrings, she does this.

00:50:40.870 --> 00:50:43.040
She's very woman here.

00:50:43.040 --> 00:50:45.310
But she also was
a strategic ruler.

00:50:45.310 --> 00:50:48.410
It didn't mean that she wanted
-- because she was, you know,

00:50:48.410 --> 00:50:50.900
dealing with you and
trading with you,

00:50:50.900 --> 00:50:53.720
that she would let
the [inaudible] be

00:50:53.720 --> 00:50:55.640
that you could come and
take over her territory

00:50:55.640 --> 00:51:01.880
because she had --
Njinga was born in 1582.

00:51:01.880 --> 00:51:05.590
The Portuguese, a few
maybe months after her --

00:51:05.590 --> 00:51:10.410
her family had to
flee from the capital.

00:51:10.410 --> 00:51:16.050
So she grew up in a situation
of, you know, being a refugee,

00:51:16.050 --> 00:51:18.150
coming back and,
you know, survival.

00:51:18.150 --> 00:51:22.810
Yeah. It was instinctive
to survive for Njinga.

00:51:22.810 --> 00:51:24.110
Yes. Yes, sir.

00:51:24.110 --> 00:51:30.920
&gt;&gt; Could you say a little more
